Started from 1993, Brac initiated to extend poverty reduction initiatives in the entire central coastal line of Bangladesh extending from Mongla in the West to the Ganges border of the East. From the beginning, the prime focus of this initiative was three clusters and the administrative capital of Barguna. These are namely Jamalpur Phenix, Shatia, and Ujar Majalgaon. Brac implemented development programs and projects here to rehabilitate with marginalized populations in Bangladesh, and to improve their comprehensive wellbeing. Conditional cash transfer was introduced by Brac in Bangladesh in 2001. and it was the first time globally that any case study on this undernourished coastal line. In the year 2008, Primestar started to popularize the conditional cash transfer, from where Brac becomes the leading organization in this practice.

Brac initiated “Income Generation” activities with fourteen festivals and incomes raised from almost 27,000 moderate and deprived farmers of those three areas. In addition, Brac made a collaboration with the 60 distinguished institutions of Bangladesh such as the Bangladesh Live Stock Office, AQI and other related academic institutions. In the following years, income per Barrow improved by seventy percent, and produced fat-cattle worth BDT 20 lakh in the last five years as well as increasing the income basket of Aharilan Bara by 10 % in 2014. 79% of Returned Home Md.
